        "text": "Genesis 37:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " as an article of commerce carried by Midianite merchants to Egypt (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 27:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), but is hardly the real balsam from Mecca (amyris opobalsamum), which during the Roman sovereignty was grown under culture in the gardens of Jericho, and which only succeeds in a climate little short of tropical. It was more likely the resina of the ancients, a gum procured from the terebinth or mastic tree (lentiscus, σχῖνος), which, acc. to Plin. h. nat. xxiv. 22, was held in esteem as a medicament for wounds (resolvitur resina ad vulnerum usus et malagmata oleo). Acc. to our passage and ",
